\section{Introduction}

The Czech premiere of Donald Knuth's multimedia organ oratorio, \emph{Fantasia Apocalyptica}, was a notable cultural and academic event connected with several historical and institutional milestones:
\begin{description}
\item[A Quarter Century:] The event formed the main part of the 25th-anniversary celebrations of \acro{FI MU}, see also \url{25.fi.muni.cz}.
\item[Honoring a Pioneer:] Donald Knuth is the first honorary doctor of Masaryk University, a title awarded in 1996 on the initiative of \acro{FI MU}.
\item[Institutional Context:] Organizing and recording the premiere reflects the faculty's long-standing association with Knuth's work and its influence on computer science and digital typography.
\item[Typographical Context:] This connection is also reflected in the visual identity of \acro{FI MU}: its logo incorporates the ligature ``\acro{FI}'' and was created using Knuth's \hologo{METAFONT} system.~\cite[Figure~2]{Sojka:2017:TSJ}
\item[The Work:] \emph{Fantasia Apocalyptica} is a composition based on the biblical \emph{Book of Revelation}. It combines musical structure with textual and visual elements, including symbolic imagery and notation, resulting in a multi-layered presentation.
\end{description}

The rest of this article describes the open-source workflow used to turn the raw footage into a high-resolution recording. Section~\ref{sec:acquisition} covers the acquisition and processing of the raw audiovisual data. Section~\ref{sec:opening-speech-and-closing-segment} describes the preparation of the opening speech and closing segment. Section~\ref{sec:panels} covers the preparation of the panels accompanying the performance. Section~\ref{sec:final-video-assembly} explains how these parts were combined into the final recording. Finally, Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} describes the screening of the finished video at \acro{FI~MU} on December~18, 2019.

\section{Audiovisual acquisition and processing}
\label{sec:acquisition}
The video and audio of the performance were acquired and preprocessed by Pavel \v{S}iler, Petr Holub\'{a}\v{r}, and students of the \acro{LEMMA} laboratory.~\cite{lemma} We normalized the video format and mixed ambient sound and Ji\v{r}\'{i} Zlatu\v{s}ka's opening speech into the audio.

\subsection{Video acquisition}
The video recording of the performance was made by Pavel \v{S}iler using a Sony~\acro{PXW-X70} camera. The footage includes Donald Knuth's lectures at \acro{FI~MU}, as well as shots of the church and organ and the opening speech by Ji\v{r}\'{i} Zlatu\v{s}ka.

\subsection{Video processing}
Although the video was acquired in a resolution of $1920\times1080$\,px at 25 frames per second (\acro{FPS}), the final recording was expected to have at least twice the resolution (\acro{4K}) and framerate (50~\acro{FPS}).

The lecture recordings were provided in a non-interlaced (progressive) format, whereas the footage of the church, organ, and opening speech was in an interlaced format. In addition, the lectures and opening speech were recorded from a tripod, in contrast to the handheld shots of the church and organ. The goal of the video processing was therefore not only to increase the resolution and framerate, but also to unify the video format and stabilize the handheld footage.
