The video was processed using the free open-source tool \acro{FF}mpeg\footnote{All \acro{FF}mpeg examples use the following output parameters for perceptually lossless compression: \texttt{-c:v libx265 -crf 17 -pix\_fmt yuv420p -c:a aac -b:a 384k -ar 44.1k}. They are omitted elsewhere for brevity.}~\cite{ffmpeg} and the open-source tool waifu2x~\cite{waifu2x}; see Figures~\ref{fig:ffmpeg-waifu2x}--\ref{fig:minterpolate-yadif}.
First, we stabilized the handheld footage using the \texttt{vidstabdetect} and \texttt{vidstab\discretionary{\textrm{-}}{}{}transform} \acro{FF}mpeg filters and then we increased the resolution and framerate as follows:\footnote{The increased resolution and framerate are only an illusion, so we use them in only about seven minutes of the 104-minute recording. The remaining 97 minutes consist of animated panels rendered in native \acro{4K} resolution at 50~\acro{FPS}.}

\begin{filecontents}[overwrite,nosearch,noheader]{example-minterpolate-frames-01.sh}
   $ ffmpeg -i input-video.mp4  -vf minterpolate \
           frame-images/%d.png
\end{filecontents}
\begin{filecontents}[overwrite,nosearch,noheader]{example-minterpolate-frames-02.sh}
   $ ffmpeg -framerate 50 -i frame-images/%d.png \
                                output-video.mp4
\end{filecontents}

\begin{itemize}
\item For interlaced video, we first increased the framerate using the \acro{FF}mpeg filter \texttt{yadif}, which interpolates missing half-frames (fields) from adjacent fields and lines. We then increased the resolution using waifu2x.
\item For non-interlaced video, we first increased the resolution using waifu2x. We then increased the framerate using the \texttt{minterpolate} \acro{FF}mpeg filter, which interpolates missing frames from adjacent frames.%
\footnote{When the camera or subject move fast, the \texttt{minterpolate} filter may produce visual artifacts near the edges of frames and objects. When processing Donald Knuth's lectures at \acro{FI MU}, we therefore first produced frame images from our video:
\begin{mintedblock}
\inputminted{bash}{example-minterpolate-frames-01.sh}
\end{mintedblock}
\noindent
We then inspected the frame images manually and deleted those in which artifacts were visible on Donald Knuth's person. Finally, we created the output video from the frame images:
\begin{mintedblock}
\inputminted{bash}{example-minterpolate-frames-02.sh}
\end{mintedblock}
\noindent
The video had a variable framerate of 25--50~\acro{FPS}, depending on the number of deleted images.}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Audio acquisition}
The audio of the performance was recorded using six microphones:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Two Zoom~\acro{H1} microphones were placed on the lectern and above the panels.
    \item Two Oktava~\acro{MK012} microphones were connected to a Zoom~\acro{H4} recorder, placed in the choir loft, and aimed toward the church.
    \item A Roland~\acro{R26} microphone and the Sony~\acro{PXW-X70} camera microphone were placed in the choir loft and aimed at the organ.
\end{itemize}

The audio was preprocessed by Petr Holub\'{a}\v{r}. The main input of their mix was the stereo recording from the Oktava~\acro{MK012} microphones. To add presence, Petr lightly mixed in the direct organ signal from the Roland~\acro{R26} microphone, applying frequency filtering to avoid undesirable phase shifts in the low-frequency range. To reduce the dynamic range, they used the digital \acro{VST} module \acro{SSL}~G-Master Buss Compressor from Waves Audio.

\subsection{Audio processing}
The audio was processed using the free open-source program Audacity; see Figure~\ref{fig:audacity}. The resulting mix includes the freely licensed sound of the bell of Constance Cathedral~\cite{edsward2016church}, the preprocessed audio of the performance from Petr Holub\'{a}\v{r}, and Ji\v{r}\'{i} Zlatu\v{s}ka's opening speech underscored by ambient sound from the Oktava~\acro{MK012} microphones.

\section{Opening speech and closing segment}
\label{sec:opening-speech-and-closing-segment}
The video of the opening speech and closing was prepared together with \v{S}imon Ma\v{c}ejovsk\'{y}.

\subsection{Editing opening and closing segments}
The video recordings of the opening speech and closing were edited by \v{S}imon Ma\v{c}ejovsk\'{y} using Sony Vegas~15. The video includes footage from Donald Knuth’s lectures at \acro{FI~MU}, shots of the church and organ, Ji\v{r}\'{i} Zlatu\v{s}ka's opening speech, and photographs by Martina Mor\'{a}vkov\'{a}.

\subsection{Opening speech subtitles}
\begin{filecontents}[overwrite,nosearch,noheader]{example-ass.sh}
 $ ffmpeg -i input-video.mp4 -vf ass=subtitles.ass \
                           video-and-subtitles.mp4
\end{filecontents}
Ji\v{r}\'{i} Zlatu\v{s}ka's opening speech was provided with subtitles in the \acro{ASS} format.\footnote{The FFmpeg filter \texttt{ass} can be used to burn subtitles into the video image:
\begin{mintedblock}
\inputminted{text}{example-ass.sh}
\end{mintedblock}
\noindent
The \texttt{ass} filter is implemented by the \texttt{libass} software library, which by default does not use the kerning table of the selected font~\cite{enable-kerning-by-default}. To enable kerning, add the line \texttt{Kerning:} \texttt{yes} to the \texttt{[Script Info]} section of the \texttt{subtitles.ass} file.} The subtitles were prepared using the free tool Aegisub~\cite{aegisub}; see Figure~\ref{fig:aegisub}.

